    "mainNotes": "## Foundations and early societies\n\nThe islands that constitute the archipelago of Cabo Verde were uninhabited by humans prior to the arrival of European explorers in the mid-fifteenth century. While historical and ecological evidence suggests that fishers from the West African mainland, including Wolof, Serer, or Lebou communities, may have visited the northern islands, they established no permanent settlements. In 1460, Portuguese mariners, including Diogo Gomes and the Genoese navigator António de Noli, reached the islands and claimed them for the Portuguese Crown. The archipelago occupied a strategic position along maritime routes connecting Europe, Africa, and the Americas. In 1462, the Portuguese established Ribeira Grande on the island of Santiago, marking the first permanent European colonial settlement in the tropics.\n\n## States, empires, and outside powers\n\nCabo Verde quickly became a central hub in the expanding transatlantic slave trade. The Portuguese Crown granted settlement incentives and trade monopolies to colonizers, who imported enslaved laborers from the West African coast to work on plantations and to be re-exported to the Americas. This convergence of Portuguese settlers and West African peoples led to the emergence of a distinct Creole culture and the Crioulo language, which became the primary medium of communication. The wealth generated by the slave trade attracted frequent raids by foreign privateers, including a notable attack by Francis Drake in 1585. Following a devastating French raid in 1712, Ribeira Grande declined in importance, and the capital was officially transferred to Praia in 1770. Recurrent droughts and famines, exacerbated by deforestation and overgrazing, plagued the islands during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, causing massive depopulation and prompting significant emigration, particularly to New England.\n\n## Formation of the modern state\n\nThe decline of the slave trade in the nineteenth century, culminating in its abolition in 1836 and the final emancipation of enslaved people in 1876, forced an economic transition. Cabo Verde became an important coaling and refueling station for transatlantic shipping, particularly at Mindelo on the island of São Vicente. In 1951, Portugal altered the legal status of the territory from a colony to an overseas province in an attempt to counter growing anti-colonial sentiment. In 1956, the intellectual Amílcar Cabral co-founded the African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde (PAIGC). Cabral advocated for a joint liberation struggle for both territories. While armed conflict raged in Guinea-Bissau during the 1960s and early 1970s, the geographic isolation and arid climate of Cabo Verde prevented the establishment of a guerrilla front on the islands, limiting the local struggle to political organizing and underground resistance.\n\n## Twentieth century\n\nThe Carnation Revolution of April 1974 in Lisbon overthrew the Portuguese dictatorial regime, leading to rapid decolonization. Cabo Verde achieved formal independence on July 5, 1975, under a transitional government led by the PAIGC. Aristides Pereira became the first president of the new republic, which operated as a one-party state. Although the constitution initially envisioned a political union with Guinea-Bissau, this plan was abandoned following a military coup in Guinea-Bissau in November 1980. In response, the Cabo Verdean branch of the ruling party severed ties and reconstituted itself as the African Party for the Independence of Cape Verde (PAICV) in 1981. Growing domestic demand for political liberalization led the PAICV to legalize opposition parties in 1990. The first multi-party legislative elections in January 1991 resulted in a victory for the Movement for Democracy (MpD), and António Mascarenhas Monteiro was elected president in a peaceful transition of power.\n\n## Recent history\n\nSince the transition of 1991, Cabo Verde has maintained a stable, multi-party democratic system characterized by regular, peaceful rotations of power between the MpD and the PAICV. The country lacks substantial natural resources and suffers from chronic freshwater scarcity, yet it has achieved significant developmental progress through effective governance, tourism, and financial support from its large global diaspora. In 2007, the United Nations formally graduated Cabo Verde from the status of a Least Developed Country to a Middle-Income Country, a rare achievement for a resource-poor island nation. In the early 2020s, the government focused on diversifying the economy, expanding renewable energy infrastructure, and mitigating the impacts of climate change, which poses an ongoing threat to the archipelago's fragile ecosystems and agricultural sector.\n\n## Key dates\n\n* 1460: Portuguese explorers document the uninhabited islands of the archipelago.\n* 1462: Portuguese settlers establish Ribeira Grande, the first permanent European settlement in the tropics.\n* 1770: Praia becomes the official capital of the colony, succeeding the declining Ribeira Grande.\n* 1876: Slavery is officially abolished throughout the Cabo Verdean archipelago.\n* 1956: Amílcar Cabral co-founds the PAIGC to campaign for independence from Portuguese rule.\n* 1975: Cabo Verde achieves full independence from Portugal on July 5.\n* 1981: The ruling party renames itself PAICV, formally abandoning the political goal of unification with Guinea-Bissau.\n* 1991: Cabo Verde holds its first multi-party democratic elections, resulting in a peaceful transition of power.\n* 2007: The United Nations graduates Cabo Verde from the category of Least Developed Countries.",
    "summary": "Uninhabited before Portuguese colonization in the fifteenth century, Cabo Verde developed as a strategic hub for the transatlantic slave trade, fostering a distinct Creole culture. Following its independence in 1975 and a transition to multi-party democracy in 1991, the nation has established a reputation for political stability and steady economic development. Despite severe environmental challenges and limited natural resources, Cabo Verde has successfully transitioned into a middle-income country.",
