    "mainNotes": "## Foundations and early societies\nThe territory of present-day Slovenia was settled long before the modern Slovene nation emerged. In pre-Roman times it was inhabited by Celtic and Illyrian groups, and by the first century BCE it was incorporated into the Roman world. Roman roads and towns connected the region to the wider empire, especially in the provinces of Noricum, Pannonia, and parts of Venetia et Histria. Important Roman settlements included Emona, Poetovio, and Celeia, which served as administrative, military, and commercial centers. After the collapse of Roman authority in the western Balkans, the area experienced migrations and shifting local rule.\n\n## States, empires, and outside powers\nIn the 6th and 7th centuries, Slavic-speaking settlers arrived and gradually formed new communities. One of the earliest known Slavic polities in the area was Carantania, centered in the eastern Alpine region around the 7th century. Carantania later came under Frankish influence and was Christianized, and by the 9th century the region was integrated into the Carolingian sphere. Over the following centuries, the Slovene lands were divided among various feudal units, including the Duchy of Carinthia, the Duchy of Styria, Carniola, Gorizia, and the coastal Adriatic cities. From the late Middle Ages onward, most of the territory came under Habsburg rule, although coastal and western areas were also affected by Venetian, Patriarchal, and later Austrian interests. Habsburg administration tied the region to the Central European imperial economy and legal order, while local elites remained mostly German-speaking or bilingual. The Protestant Reformation briefly strengthened Slovene literacy, but Counter-Reformation pressure limited its reach. The first substantial Slovene-language printed works appeared in the 16th century, notably those associated with Primož Trubar, who helped standardize written Slovene.\n\n## Formation of the modern state\nThe modern Slovene nation developed in the 18th and 19th centuries through language standardization, education, and political awakening. The Enlightenment and later Romantic nationalism encouraged the idea of a distinct Slovene people within the Habsburg monarchy. During the Napoleonic period, the Illyrian Provinces, created in 1809, placed much of the area under French rule for a short time and promoted administrative reform and the use of local languages. After 1815 the Congress of Vienna restored Austrian control, but modern political life continued to expand. In the 1848 revolutions, Slovene intellectuals advanced the idea of a united Slovenia, meaning the political unification of Slovene-speaking lands inside the Habsburg framework. The demand was not fully realized, yet it became a lasting national program.\n\nLate 19th-century industrialization, railway expansion, and urbanization strengthened Ljubljana, Maribor, Celje, and the Adriatic port of Trieste, though the Slovene-speaking population remained divided among imperial provinces. Political life increasingly centered on Catholic, liberal, and socialist movements, and mass politics deepened the use of Slovene in schools, newspapers, and associations. After World War I and the collapse of Austria-Hungary in 1918, most Slovene lands entered the new State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs and then the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes, later Yugoslavia. The postwar settlement did not unite all Slovene-speaking areas, since parts remained in Italy and Austria.\n\n## Twentieth century\nIn interwar Yugoslavia, Slovene politics operated within a centralized monarchy that often constrained regional autonomy. Economic development continued, but political tensions grew between centralist and federalist visions. The period also saw border disputes and minority pressures in areas assigned to Italy and Austria. During World War II, Slovenia was invaded and partitioned in 1941 by Germany, Italy, Hungary, and the Independent State of Croatia. The occupation brought violent repression, deportations, collaboration, and resistance. The Communist-led partisan movement became the dominant force in liberation politics, and after 1945 Slovenia became one of the six republics of socialist Yugoslavia.\n\nUnder socialist rule, the republic experienced rapid industrialization, urban growth, and social modernization, alongside one-party governance and political repression. Yugoslavia’s break with Stalin in 1948 gave the country a more independent position in the Cold War, and Slovenia benefited from relative openness, trade with Western Europe, and labor migration. The 1974 Yugoslav constitution expanded republican autonomy, which later became important for Slovenian political reforms. By the late 1980s, economic crisis, demands for democratization, and debates over federal reform intensified. Slovene intellectuals, civic groups, and party reformers pushed for pluralism, market reform, and greater sovereignty.\n\n## Recent history\nIn 1990 Slovenia held its first multiparty elections, and in June 1991 it declared independence from Yugoslavia. A short conflict known as the Ten-Day War followed, after which Yugoslav forces withdrew and the new state retained effective control over most of its territory. International recognition followed in 1992, and Slovenia steadily built democratic institutions, a market economy, and a professional civil service. The transition years brought privatization, restructuring of industry, and growth in services, though also debates over inequality and ownership change.\n\nSlovenia oriented itself toward European and transatlantic institutions. It joined NATO and the European Union in 2004, adopted the euro in 2007, and entered the Schengen Area in 2007, reflecting its integration into Western European political and economic systems. The global financial crisis affected banks and growth, and subsequent years brought fiscal consolidation and slower but stable development. Public debate often centered on corruption, welfare policy, pension reform, and the balance between urban and regional interests. By the early 2020s Slovenia was a parliamentary democracy with a mixed economy, strong trade links to the EU, and a political identity shaped by the legacies of Habsburg rule, Yugoslav socialism, and the independence transition.\n\n## Key dates\n- c. 1st century BCE to 1st century CE: Roman rule incorporated the area into provinces such as Noricum, Pannonia, and Venetia et Histria.\n- c. 7th century: Slavic settlement led to the emergence of Carantania and related early medieval communities.\n- 9th century: Frankish control and Christianization tied the region to the Carolingian world.\n- 1809 to 1813: The Napoleonic Illyrian Provinces introduced short-lived French administration and reforms.\n- 1848: Slovene national demands for a united Slovenia became a major political program.\n- 1918: Most Slovene lands entered the new South Slav state after the collapse of Austria-Hungary.\n- 1941 to 1945: Slovenia was partitioned and occupied during World War II.\n- 1945: Slovenia became a republic within socialist Yugoslavia.\n- 25 June 1991: Slovenia declared independence from Yugoslavia.\n- 2004: Slovenia joined NATO and the European Union.",
    "summary": "Slovenia’s history moves from Roman and early medieval borderlands through centuries of Habsburg rule to the growth of a Slovene national movement in the 19th century. The modern state emerged from Yugoslavia in 1991 after a brief war, then integrated rapidly into European and transatlantic institutions while maintaining a parliamentary democracy and export-oriented economy.",
