    "mainNotes": "## Foundations and early societies\nBarbados was inhabited long before European arrival. Archaeological evidence shows repeated settlement by Indigenous peoples from South America, including Archaic and later Saladoid and Arawak-speaking communities, who fished, farmed, and used the island’s coastal resources. By the time Europeans arrived, the island had likely been affected by shifting migration and conflict in the wider Lesser Antilles, and its resident population was smaller than on some neighboring islands. The name Barbados is usually linked to Portuguese or Spanish explorers who referred to the island’s bearded fig trees.\n\n## States, empires, and outside powers\nSpanish and Portuguese vessels passed the island in the late 15th and early 16th centuries, but neither empire established a durable settlement. England claimed Barbados in 1625, and English colonists founded a settlement at Holetown in 1627. Early colonial agriculture grew tobacco, cotton, and food crops, but by the mid-17th century Barbados had become one of the British Caribbean’s most profitable sugar colonies. Large plantation estates expanded rapidly, and the island developed a rigid social order based on land ownership, political privilege, and enslaved labor.\n\nThe plantation economy depended heavily on the forced migration of Africans. Enslaved people soon formed the majority of the population and were central to the island’s wealth, culture, and resistance history. Barbados was a major site in the Atlantic slave system, and its economy became closely linked to London merchants, credit networks, and imperial trade rules. The island also had strategic military value. During the Anglo-Dutch rivalry and later imperial wars, Barbados remained firmly under English and then British control, unlike some Caribbean islands that changed hands repeatedly.\n\nColonial political institutions were unusually stable. The House of Assembly, created in 1639, became one of the oldest representative bodies in the English-speaking Americas, though its electorate was restricted to white property owners for most of the colonial era. Britain’s imperial reforms in the nineteenth century gradually altered this system, especially after slavery ended and plantation society adjusted to wage labor, migration, and falling sugar profits.\n\n## Formation of the modern state\nBarbados did not unite with neighboring territories, and its present borders largely reflect the island colony established in the 17th century. The end of slavery came with the British Emancipation Act, which took effect in 1834; most formerly enslaved people then passed through an apprenticeship period until 1838, when full emancipation was completed. Formerly enslaved Barbadians and their descendants created villages, churches, mutual aid groups, and a laboring peasantry, while many people continued to work on estates or in low-paid urban jobs.\n\nFormal constitutional development moved slowly. In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the island remained a British colony with limited self-rule and a small elite-controlled electorate. Broader political participation grew only after labor unrest and pressure for reform in the 1930s and 1940s. Barbados became a separate British colony in 1885 after the dissolution of the short-lived British West Indian federal arrangements in the 19th century’s imperial administration, and later constitutional changes prepared the way for modern parliamentary democracy.\n\n## Twentieth century\nThe twentieth century brought major political and social transformation. The 1937 labor disturbances, associated with widespread unemployment, low wages, and poor living conditions, helped spur the rise of mass politics and trade union organizing. Grantley Adams emerged as a leading reform figure, and the Barbados Labour Party, founded in 1944, became an important vehicle for constitutional change. Expanded suffrage in the mid-20th century opened politics to a much larger share of the population.\n\nIn 1958 Barbados joined the West Indies Federation, a British-backed attempt to unite several Caribbean colonies into a single state. The federation collapsed in 1962 after disagreements among the member territories, and Barbados returned to separate constitutional development. Self-government increased in 1961, and on 30 November 1966 Barbados became independent within the Commonwealth with Errol Barrow as its first prime minister. The new state retained the British monarch as head of state, while local institutions controlled domestic affairs. Independence was accompanied by a policy of social development, including education, health services, and efforts to diversify an economy still tied to sugar and external markets.\n\n## Recent history\nAfter independence, Barbados built a reputation for political stability, regular elections, and comparatively strong public administration. The two-party system centered on the Barbados Labour Party and the Democratic Labour Party. Economic change gradually reduced the dominance of sugar, while tourism, offshore services, light manufacturing, and international business became more important. Social policy emphasized literacy, schooling, and public health, helping Barbados attain some of the highest human development indicators in the region.\n\nBarbados also played a visible role in Caribbean diplomacy and regional integration through the Caribbean Community and other organizations. At the same time, the island faced the wider challenges of small-state development, including vulnerability to external shocks, debt pressures, and climate-related risks such as coastal erosion and hurricanes. By the early 2020s, national debate increasingly focused on economic resilience, reparatory justice, and constitutional identity.\n\nA major constitutional change came on 30 November 2021, when Barbados removed the British monarch as head of state and became a parliamentary republic. The transition preserved the parliamentary system and Commonwealth membership while replacing the governor general with a Barbadian president. This change reflected long-standing discussions about decolonization and national self-definition rather than a break with democratic institutions.\n\n## Key dates\n- c. 1625: England claimed Barbados, beginning permanent European imperial control.\n- 1627: English settlers founded Holetown, the first lasting colonial settlement.\n- 1639: The House of Assembly first met, forming an early colonial legislature.\n- Mid-17th century: Sugar plantation slavery expanded, making Barbados a major Caribbean slave society.\n- 1834 to 1838: Slavery ended under emancipation, followed by apprenticeship and then full freedom.\n- 1937: Labor unrest accelerated mass politics, union growth, and demands for reform.\n- 1958 to 1962: Barbados participated in the West Indies Federation until the federation dissolved.\n- 1961: Barbados achieved internal self-government.\n- 30 November 1966: Barbados became independent within the Commonwealth.\n- 30 November 2021: Barbados became a parliamentary republic and removed the British monarch as head of state.",
    "summary": "Barbados developed from Indigenous settlement into a highly profitable British sugar colony built on enslaved African labor, then evolved into a stable parliamentary democracy after emancipation, labor reform, and decolonization. Its modern history is marked by independence in 1966, economic diversification beyond sugar, and the 2021 transition from monarchy to republic while retaining Commonwealth ties.",
