    "mainNotes": "## Foundations and early societies\nDominica was first inhabited by Indigenous peoples of the Caribbean long before European contact. The earliest known residents were related to the Ciboney and later Arawakan-speaking peoples, followed by Kalinago, also known as Island Caribs, who by the late pre-Columbian period controlled much of the island. Dominica’s mountainous terrain and limited sheltered harbors helped preserve Kalinago autonomy longer than on many neighboring islands. The island became a center of resistance to European expansion, and Kalinago communities remained an important part of its social history even after colonization.\n\n## States, empires, and outside powers\nChristopher Columbus sighted Dominica on 3 November 1493, but Spain did not establish a permanent colony there. For more than a century, Kalinago resistance and the island’s difficult terrain discouraged lasting settlement. In the seventeenth century, French planters and traders began to exert growing influence, and by the mid-1700s Dominica had become a contested frontier between France and Britain. The island was formally ceded to Britain by the Treaty of Paris in 1763, though France temporarily regained it during later European wars. British rule became more durable after the Treaty of Versailles in 1783. Under colonial rule, plantation agriculture expanded, especially coffee, later sugar, and other export crops, based largely on enslaved African labor. The enslaved population greatly outnumbered Europeans, and resistance took many forms, including maroonage, flight, and occasional armed revolt. After the abolition of slavery in the British Empire in 1834, a period of apprenticeship was followed by full emancipation in 1838, but land ownership and political power remained concentrated among a small colonial elite.\n\n## Formation of the modern state\nIn 1833 Dominica became a separate British colony, distinct from the larger administrative units that had previously governed it. During the nineteenth century the colonial state was reshaped by reforms that expanded the rights of free people of color and by the gradual decline of plantation profitability. Small farmers, wage laborers, and village communities became more important in the island economy. In 1958 Dominica entered the short-lived West Indies Federation, which aimed to unite several British Caribbean territories into one political federation; when that project collapsed in 1962, Dominica returned to separate colonial administration. Constitutional change followed through associated statehood in 1967, which gave Dominica control over internal affairs while Britain retained responsibility for defense and foreign policy. On 3 November 1978, Dominica became an independent republic within the Commonwealth, creating the modern sovereign state and preserving its colonial-era land borders with the French territories of Guadeloupe to the north and Martinique to the south across maritime boundaries.\n\n## Twentieth century\nThe twentieth century was marked by slow economic diversification and a gradual widening of political participation. Banana production became central to the economy after the Second World War, especially through smallholder farming, and export earnings tied the island closely to British and later European markets. Labor politics and constitutional reform gained importance as universal suffrage and party competition developed. Dominica experienced serious social unrest in the 1970s, including the riots of 1979, which reflected tensions over governance, inequality, and the pace of reform. Independence in 1978 was followed by a difficult transition, including the brief government of Patrick John, a former leader of the independence movement whose administration fell after the unrest. The years that followed saw institutional consolidation under elected governments, but also recurring debates over development strategy, foreign investment, and the balance between state intervention and private enterprise.\n\n## Recent history\nSince the 1980s Dominica has remained a parliamentary democracy and a member of the Organization of Eastern Caribbean States, CARICOM, the Commonwealth, and the United Nations. Its economy has depended on bananas, tourism, public services, and remittances, while governments have sought to reduce vulnerability to external markets and repeated natural disasters. Dominica was badly affected by Hurricane David in 1979 and later by other storms, but Hurricane Maria in September 2017 caused especially severe damage, destroying housing, crops, roads, and power systems across much of the island. Recovery efforts in the 2010s and early 2020s emphasized climate resilience, rebuilding infrastructure, and diversifying the economy through ecotourism and renewable energy projects. In foreign policy, Dominica has generally favored Caribbean regional cooperation, relations with both Western and non-Western partners, and strong advocacy on climate change and disaster vulnerability for small island states. The island’s history in the early twenty-first century has therefore been shaped by democratic continuity, environmental risk, and efforts to build a more resilient post-plantation economy.\n\n## Key dates\n- around 1493: Christopher Columbus sighted Dominica during his second voyage, bringing the island into European geographic knowledge.\n- 1763: France ceded Dominica to Britain in the Treaty of Paris, making British rule the dominant colonial authority.\n- 1783: The Treaty of Versailles confirmed British control after renewed conflict with France.\n- 1833: Dominica became a separate British colony, distinct from neighboring colonial administrative arrangements.\n- 1834 to 1838: Slavery ended in stages with apprenticeship and then full emancipation.\n- 1958 to 1962: Dominica participated in the West Indies Federation until the federation dissolved.\n- 1967: Dominica gained associated statehood and internal self-government.\n- 3 November 1978: Dominica became an independent state within the Commonwealth.\n- 1979: Hurricane David and political unrest severely disrupted the new state.\n- September 2017: Hurricane Maria caused catastrophic island-wide damage and accelerated debates over resilience and reconstruction.",
    "summary": "Dominica’s history moves from Kalinago settlement and resistance to a long colonial contest between France and Britain, followed by British plantation rule based on enslaved labor. The modern state emerged through decolonization in the mid-twentieth century, culminating in independence in 1978.\n\nSince independence, Dominica has remained a parliamentary democracy while facing economic dependence on agriculture, regional migration, and repeated hurricane damage. Its recent history has been defined by efforts to diversify the economy, strengthen resilience, and maintain active Caribbean and international cooperation.",
