    "cues": [
      "Who lived on Hispaniola before European colonization?",
      "Why did the Spanish and French both claim parts of Hispaniola?",
      "What was the impact of Haitian rule on the eastern side of the island?",
      "How did the Dominican Republic first achieve independence in 1844?",
      "What was the annexation to Spain, and why did it end?",
      "How did the U.S. occupation shape Dominican politics and the military?",
      "What characterized the Trujillo era and its legacy?",
      "What major democratic and economic changes marked the late twentieth and early twenty-first centuries?"
    ],
    "mainNotes": "## Foundations and early societies\nBefore European contact, the island of Hispaniola was inhabited by Indigenous peoples, especially the Taíno, who lived in chiefdoms organized around local rulers. Their societies practiced agriculture, fishing, and inter-island trade, and they developed political and religious systems adapted to the Caribbean environment. The population was devastated after 1492 by warfare, forced labor, displacement, and disease brought by Europeans.\n\n## States, empires, and outside powers\nChristopher Columbus landed on Hispaniola in 1492, and the Spanish quickly established settlements on the eastern side of the island. Santo Domingo, founded in 1496, became the oldest permanent European settlement in the Americas and the center of Spanish administration in the region. Spanish control over the eastern part of the island gradually weakened as colonial priorities shifted to other areas, while France expanded on the western side. By the late seventeenth century, Spanish and French influence had settled into a divided island, formalized by treaties that recognized French rule in the west and Spanish rule in the east.\n\nDuring the early nineteenth century, the eastern colony experienced repeated political change. Spain briefly restored direct rule, but in 1821 local elites declared independence from Spain in a short-lived state known as Spanish Haiti. In 1822 Haitian forces under Jean-Pierre Boyer unified the island under Haitian administration. Haitian rule brought the abolition of slavery and new land policies, but it also generated opposition among eastern elites and many residents who resented centralized control and taxation.\n\n## Formation of the modern state\nDominican independence began on 27 February 1844, when the secret society La Trinitaria, led by Juan Pablo Duarte, Francisco del Rosario Sánchez, and Matías Ramón Mella, helped drive out Haitian rule and proclaim a separate Dominican Republic. The new state was weak, faced military pressure from Haiti, and struggled with internal rivalries between constitutionalists and strong military caudillos. In 1849 and again in the 1850s, Dominican leaders sought foreign protection, showing how insecure sovereignty remained.\n\nIn 1861 President Pedro Santana arranged annexation to Spain, a controversial move intended to secure defense and stability. Resistance culminated in the War of Restoration beginning in 1863, a nationalist guerrilla struggle that forced Spain to withdraw in 1865 and restored the republic. The new state’s borders were shaped by this conflict and by later negotiations with Haiti, though disputes and cross-border movement remained a long-term feature of the island.\n\n## Twentieth century\nThe early twentieth century was marked by debt, instability, and growing U.S. influence. The United States occupied the Dominican Republic from 1916 to 1924, taking control of customs and finances and reorganizing the armed forces. One major consequence was the creation of a centralized constabulary that later helped support authoritarian rule.\n\nRafael Trujillo came to power in 1930 and ruled until his assassination in 1961. His regime was a dictatorship built on censorship, repression, patronage, and an extensive cult of personality. Trujillo promoted infrastructure and state modernization, but political violence and fear defined the era. In 1937 his government ordered the massacre of thousands of Haitians and Haitian-Dominicans near the border, a central event in Dominican-Haitian relations. After Trujillo’s death, the country entered a turbulent transition, including the elected government of Juan Bosch in 1963, its overthrow, and the civil war of 1965. The United States intervened again in 1965, and a negotiated settlement led to constitutional rule under Joaquín Balaguer and later civilian governments.\n\n## Recent history\nFrom the late twentieth century into the early 2020s, the Dominican Republic experienced gradual democratization, economic diversification, and closer integration with global markets. Tourism, export-processing zones, construction, remittances, and services became major parts of the economy alongside older agricultural exports such as sugar. Migration from Haiti and the United States became a major social and political issue, especially in border regions and urban labor markets.\n\nPolitics became more competitive after the 1978 transfer of power away from Balaguer’s long-standing dominance, though his influence persisted into the 1990s. Constitutional reforms and regular elections strengthened civilian institutions, while corruption, inequality, and clientelism remained persistent concerns. The 1990s and 2000s also saw expansion in infrastructure, telecommunications, and education, along with vulnerability to hurricanes and economic shocks.\n\nA major regional crisis came after the 2010 Haiti earthquake and later court and administrative changes affecting people of Haitian descent and their descendants in the Dominican Republic, which drew domestic and international criticism over nationality and statelessness. In the 2010s and early 2020s, the country maintained democratic elections, continued tourism growth, and faced the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic, which disrupted travel and exposed inequality but did not end the long trend toward a more service-based economy.\n\n## Key dates\n- 1492: Columbus reached Hispaniola, beginning Spanish colonization of the island.\n- 1496: Santo Domingo was founded and became the main Spanish center in the Caribbean.\n- 1697: The Treaty of Ryswick recognized French control of the western part of Hispaniola and Spanish control of the east.\n- 1821: The eastern colony declared short-lived independence from Spain as Spanish Haiti.\n- 1822: Haitian forces unified Hispaniola under Haitian rule.\n- 27 February 1844: Dominican independence was proclaimed after a rebellion against Haitian control.\n- 1861 to 1865: The republic was annexed to Spain, then restored after the War of Restoration.\n- 1916 to 1924: The United States occupied the Dominican Republic and reorganized its finances and security forces.\n- 1930 to 1961: Rafael Trujillo ruled as dictator, shaping modern Dominican politics through repression and centralization.\n- 1965: Civil war and a U.S. intervention marked a turning point toward later constitutional politics.\n- 1978: An ընդդ? Actually need no typos",
    "summary": "The Dominican Republic’s history is shaped by Indigenous Taíno society, Spanish colonization of the eastern Hispaniola, and repeated struggles over sovereignty with Haiti, Spain, and the United States. Modern statehood emerged in 1844, but political instability, dictatorship under Trujillo, and later democratization defined much of the twentieth century.\n\nSince the late 1900s, the country has become more democratic and economically diversified, especially through tourism, services, and remittances. At the same time, migration, inequality, and tensions over nationality and the Haitian border have remained central issues into the early 2020s.",
