    "mainNotes": "## Foundations and early societies\nTonga was settled by Austronesian-speaking Lapita peoples around 3000 years ago, making it one of the earliest places in Polynesia to be permanently inhabited. Archaeology shows a society based on gardening, fishing, canoe travel, and exchange across island groups. Over time, local chiefs developed ranked lineages and ritual authority, and Tonga became a major center of Polynesian migration and political influence. The earliest settlements on Tongatapu and nearby islands laid the basis for later chiefly institutions.\n\nBy the first millennium CE, Tonga had become the core of a complex chiefly system often associated with the Tuʻi Tonga line. The Tuʻi Tonga were sacred rulers whose prestige extended through diplomacy, marriage alliances, trade, and tribute rather than direct administration alone. Monumental architecture, including langi burial mounds and stone structures, reflected accumulated authority and social hierarchy. Tongan navigators and elites participated in far-reaching networks linking Samoa, Fiji, Uvea, and other parts of Polynesia.\n\n## States, empires, and outside powers\nFrom roughly the 10th to 15th centuries, the Tuʻi Tonga polity reached its height and exerted influence across much of western Polynesia. Later, internal rivalries and succession disputes led to new chiefly branches, including the Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua and Tuʻi Kanokupolu, which shared and redistributed power. This evolution produced a more politically layered society in which ritual rank, military strength, and local chiefly control all mattered.\n\nEuropean contact began in the 17th century and intensified in the 18th century. Dutch explorers Abel Tasman in 1643 and James Cook in 1773 and 1777 were among the best-known early visitors, and Cook described Tonga as the \"Friendly Islands\" because of the welcoming reception he observed. In practice, contact brought new trade goods, firearms, disease, and growing foreign religious influence, while Tongan leaders used outside contacts selectively to strengthen their own positions.\n\nIn the early 19th century, Protestant missionaries from the London Missionary Society and later the Wesleyan tradition gained influence, especially among rulers and elites. Christianity spread rapidly and reshaped political culture, literacy, and law. The arrival of weapons and competition among chiefs intensified conflict, but it also created conditions for stronger central rule under a single dynastic line.\n\n## Formation of the modern state\nTaufaʻahau, later King George Tupou I, emerged as the key unifier of Tonga in the mid-19th century. Through warfare, alliance building, and conversion to Christianity, he consolidated control over most of the archipelago and curtailed rival chiefly powers. In 1845 he assumed the title of Tuʻi Kanokupolu and later moved to centralize authority in a modernizing monarchy.\n\nThe 1875 Constitution, promulgated under George Tupou I with the help of missionary adviser Shirley Waldemar Baker, transformed Tonga into a constitutional monarchy. It established a written legal order, declared equality before the law, reorganized land tenure, and created institutions for parliament and government while preserving the king's central role. Tonga was never formally annexed as a colony, but it entered a British protected state arrangement in 1900 through the Treaty of Friendship, which left internal self-government in place while placing foreign affairs under British oversight.\n\n## Twentieth century\nDuring the protectorate period, Tonga retained its monarchy and much of its internal legal system, unlike many neighboring island territories that were directly colonized. British influence grew in diplomacy and administration, and missionaries and educated Tongan elites continued to shape social life. The economy remained based on agriculture, especially copra and later squash, and on remittances from Tongans abroad.\n\nAfter World War II, pressure for administrative modernization increased, but the monarchy and chiefly system remained dominant. Tonga joined regional and international organizations, including the United Nations in 1999, and gradually expanded education, infrastructure, and wage employment. Political debate increasingly centered on the limited size of the elected legislature and the balance between noble privilege and popular representation.\n\nIn 1970 Tonga ended British protection and became fully independent while maintaining the monarchy and constitution. The state adopted a cautious foreign policy, balancing ties with New Zealand, Australia, Britain, the United States, and neighboring Pacific states. Tonga also developed a large diaspora, and remittances became a major part of household incomes and the national economy.\n\n## Recent history\nFrom the 1990s onward, reform movements called for greater democratic representation, faster accountability, and limits on the power of nobles and the executive. Social pressure grew through churches, civic groups, and a more politically engaged educated class. In 2010 the constitution was revised so that a majority of seats in the Legislative Assembly would be elected by the people, marking the most important political reform since independence, although the monarchy retained significant authority.\n\nThe country experienced episodes of unrest and disruption, including political tensions and the 2006 riots in Nukuʻalofa, which caused serious damage to the capital and accelerated rebuilding and reform debates. Tonga also faced major natural disasters: the 2009 tsunami, Tropical Cyclone Gita in 2018, and the Hunga Tonga-Hunga Haʻapai volcanic eruption and tsunami in January 2022, which severely affected infrastructure, communications, and livelihoods. These events highlighted the country's vulnerability as a small island state and the importance of regional and international assistance.\n\nEconomically, Tonga remained dependent on remittances, aid, tourism, and a narrow export base, with ongoing concerns about youth employment, emigration, and climate change. Despite these pressures, the state preserved its constitutional monarchy, Pacific alliances, and distinct cultural institutions into the early 2020s.\n\n## Key dates\n- c. 1000 BCE to 300 BCE: Lapita-associated settlers establish the earliest known communities in Tonga.\n- c. 950 to 1200 CE: The Tuʻi Tonga polity expands and becomes a major regional power in Polynesia.\n- 1643: Abel Tasman becomes the first recorded European to sight parts of Tonga.\n- 1773 to 1777: James Cook visits Tonga and popularizes the name \"Friendly Islands.\"\n- 1845: Taufaʻahau unifies the islands more firmly and becomes King George Tupou I.\n- 1875: Tonga receives its written constitution, creating a constitutional monarchy.\n- 1900: Tonga becomes a British protected state under the Treaty of Friendship.\n- 1970: Tonga gains full independence while keeping the monarchy and constitution.\n- 2010: Electoral reform expands popular representation in the Legislative Assembly.\n- 2022: The Hunga Tonga-Hunga Haʻapai eruption and tsunami cause severe national damage.",
    "summary": "Tonga developed from early Lapita settlement into a powerful Polynesian chiefly center led by the Tuʻi Tonga and later reorganized under a unifying monarchy. Unlike many Pacific neighbors, it was never fully colonized, instead becoming a British protected state before gaining independence in 1970.\n\nIn the modern era, Tonga combined constitutional monarchy with gradual political reform, growing diaspora remittances, and strong Christian and chiefly institutions. Recent history has been shaped by democratization efforts, unrest in 2006, and repeated natural disasters that exposed the country’s vulnerability while reinforcing the importance of regional ties.",
